taxonomy_info.title: Collaborative Action Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating clear, specific next steps with appropriate student input rather than imposing predetermined paths, ensuring mutual ownership of decisions.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants develop action plans that include both consultant and student responsibilities with clear timelines and mutual agreement.
examples: Consultant: "So our plan is: I'll send you the detailed program information today, you'll review it by Thursday, and we'll have another call Friday to finalize your approach. Does that timeline work for you?"
Consultant: "Based on our discussion, you'll start with 2 units in your first teaching period, and we'll evaluate how that's working after the first month. Are you comfortable with that approach?"

Consultant: "Let's agree on next steps: you'll speak with your employer about study support, I'll prepare the enrollment information tailored to what we've discussed, and we'll reconvene next week. Sound good?"

taxonomy_info.title: Teaching Period Selection Objection Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about recommended start dates or teaching period timing through explanation of benefits and exploration of alternatives within actual program structure.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students express disappointment or concern about suggested start dates or timing recommendations.
examples: Student: "I was hoping to start in February, but it sounds like you're suggesting I wait until July. That's a long time to wait, and I'm concerned about losing momentum."
Consultant: "I understand your concern about the timing. Let me explain why July might actually work better for your situation and explore if there are any alternatives that align with your goals"
Consultant: "You can enroll now and defer to the next teaching period if needed, giving you flexibility while securing your place"

taxonomy_info.title: Process Clarification Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of making complex application or enrollment processes accessible through step-by-step explanation and verification.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants break down processes into manageable components and check for understanding.
examples: Consultant: "Let me explain the three-step process: First, submit your transcript by Friday. This ensures we verify eligibility before the deadline. Second, complete the online form. Third, we'll have a brief call to finalize everything"
Consultant: "Does that make sense? Would you like me to clarify anything about these steps?"
Consultant: "So pretty much after this call, I'll send you the application link. Once you've started your application, you'll get a welcome email..."

taxonomy_info.title: Follow-Up Scheduling Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of establishing specific dates, times, and methods for follow-up interactions that maintain enrollment momentum.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants schedule specific follow-up calls or interactions with clear purposes rather than leaving contact open-ended.
examples: Consultant: "I'll call you this Friday at 3pm to check on your document progress and answer any questions"
Consultant: "Let's schedule our next call for [date and time]. Does that work for you?"
Consultant: "Would you be looking to study this this year? I'll keep that one active then" (negative example - lacks specific follow-up)

taxonomy_info.title: Appropriate Acknowledgment Depth
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of providing sufficient acknowledgment of student concerns with moderate reflection that validates their experience without overanalyzing.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants provide targeted, specific acknowledgment that clearly demonstrates understanding while maintaining forward progress in the conversation.
examples: Consultant: "Yeah, absolutely. You can take up to six deferrals throughout the master program if need be. You're more than welcome to take several study breaks"

Consultant: "I think even the best students, you know, with balancing work and family as well, would find it difficult here and there. It's always a challenge, no matter how good your work ethic is, so yeah, that's completely understandable"
Consultant: "But it's absolutely understandable being nervous about online study"

taxonomy_info.title: Urgency & Momentum Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating appropriate urgency around enrollment actions while connecting to specific benefits or deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who create time-sensitive motivation through real deadlines, benefits of early action, or consequences of delay.
examples: Consultant: "Following this timeline ensures we complete everything before the May 20th deadline and gives you priority access to unit selection"
Consultant: "Since you're asking about payment options, it sounds like you're thinking seriously about moving forward. The May 5th intake still has places available"
Consultant: "Enrolling today ensures you'll have full access to orientation materials two weeks before classes start"

taxonomy_info.title: Flexible Timeline Development
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of collaboratively planning study timelines and teaching period selections that accommodate the student's personal and professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants work with students to determine optimal timing for enrollment and progression rather than pushing predetermined schedules.
examples: Consultant: "Let's think about your work project timeline and when you'd feel most ready to take on study commitments"
Consultant: "With your current circumstances, would starting in July or November align better with your other commitments?"
Consultant: "Based on your goals and constraints, let's map out a timeline that feels achievable for your situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Responsive Adaptability
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of showing appropriate responsiveness to meaningful student signals and adjusting approach based on clear student cues without overreacting to minor signals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants demonstrate reasonable responsiveness to student signals while balancing structure with flexibility in response to student cues.
examples: Consultant: "I notice you hesitated when I mentioned the group work component. Would you like me to explain more about how that works?"
Consultant: "And in terms of your motivation to do this course, what was it that really sparked your interest in pursuing this one?"
Consultant: "You seem to have some specific questions about the online format. What aspects would be most helpful for me to clarify?"

taxonomy_info.title: Context-Informed Planning Initiation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of using previously gathered information about the student's background, goals, and preferences to guide planning discussions without repetitive questioning.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who reference earlier conversation elements when initiating planning discussions and build on established context rather than starting from scratch.
examples: Consultant: "Based on what you've shared about your work schedule and career goals, let's explore how we might structure your study approach"
Consultant: "Given your nursing background that you mentioned and your interest in leadership roles, there are a couple of pathways we should consider"
Consultant: "You've told me about your rotating shifts and family commitments, so let's look at options that would work with those realities"

taxonomy_info.title: Browsing Without Intent Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing situations where students are exploring options without clear enrollment intent, focusing on moving them toward decision-making clarity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to students who indicate they're "just looking," comparing multiple options, or not ready to commit to enrollment discussions.
examples: Student: "I'm just browsing at the moment, not really ready to make any decisions."
Consultant: "I appreciate you being upfront about that. Even when browsing, it's helpful to understand what specific information would be most valuable for your decision-making process"

Consultant: "That's completely understandable. Many students benefit from having all the information before they're ready to decide. What aspects of the program are most important for you to understand?"

enrolled_retained.justification: The consultant utilizes previously gathered information about the student's background to guide the planning discussion, specifically targeting the student's work schedule and career goals to direct the conversation. This demonstrates context-informed planning initiation as the consultant does not repeat questions but builds on established information.

not_enrolled.evidence: STUDENT: I'm just waiting on... With full transparency, I've also applied at Sydney Uni and I think they recognize experience, like. Work experience. I just wanted to get an outcome from them if they will do that for me, otherwise I will go with you guys.
not_enrolled.justification: The student expresses uncertainty about committing to Monash University due to an ongoing application with Sydney Uni, indicating they are comparing options and awaiting a preferred offer. This behavior highlights a browsing without intent to fully commit at the present moment.

not_enrolled.evidence: STUDENT: I just received a couple of calls from you.
not_enrolled.justification: The student indicates they've been receiving calls but hasn't committed to enrollment yet, while the consultant urges enrollment during the call. This behavior reflects the browsing without intent response, where the consultant attempts to move the student towards decision-making by facilitating immediate enrollment.

enrolled_not_retained.evidence: STUDENT: I've just finished my double degree of sports science and business management, and I guess I was just kind of looking around and not 100% sure on my career path, so I was just having a look at some other pathways and further learning that I could really go into, I guess the MBA was just something that I was interested in.
enrolled_not_retained.justification: The student expresses uncertainty about their career path and mentions 'just looking around,' indicating they are exploring educational options without a clear intent to enroll. This aligns with the consultant's role to respond to students who are 'just looking' and uncertain, and provide information to facilitate decision-making clarity.

enrolled_not_retained.evidence: STUDENT: I'm looking at potentially time-wise I'm looking at investing a potentially four to five years. CONSULTANT: That's correct.
enrolled_not_retained.justification: The student discusses the long-term commitment and timespan involved, typical of a general inquiry phase where they are assessing educational options. The consultant confirms this information, enabling the student to gain clarity about the program duration essential for decision-making.

enrolled_retained.evidence: STUDENT: My thing is, if I'm dicking around too much, I've just had, this one's a fully paid, where I have to pay the whole thing. You know, there's three other unis with government funded places, and I'll, you know, while I'm waiting over Christmas to sort things out. I'll end up applying there too and see where I get to first. CONSULTANT: Yeah, of course, of course. And I'm with you, see if I were you I'll do the same...
enrolled_retained.justification: The student expresses intention to explore other options due to the cost and payment model at Monash, demonstrating browsing behavior without clear enrollment intent. The consultant mirrors the student's approach to exploring all options and encourages applying to Monash with no immediate commitment, promoting clarity in decision-making.

enrolled_retained.evidence: CONSULTANT: Are you still looking through our graduate diploma in psychology?
enrolled_retained.justification: The consultant responds to a situation where the student appears to be browsing, expressing confusion about program options and seeking clarification. The consultant acknowledges the student's uncertainty and offers detailed information to guide their decision-making process toward clarity.
